      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is self-employment tax?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Self-employment tax is the Social Security and Medicare tax that self-employed individuals pay. Employees split FICA contributions with their employer at 7.65% each. Self-employed individuals pay both sides, totaling 15.3%, though they can deduct half on their federal return.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Who pays self-employment tax?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Generally anyone with net earnings from self-employment of $400 or more must pay SE tax. This includes freelancers, independent contractors, sole proprietors, gig workers, and some partners and LLC members.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Why is only 92.35% of net profit subject to SE tax?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The IRS allows you to reduce net self-employment income by 7.65% before calculating SE tax. This mirrors how an employee's wages are reduced by the employer's FICA contribution. It creates parity between employees and self-employed individuals.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does this calculator include federal income tax?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. This calculator estimates SE tax only. You may also owe federal income tax on your net self-employment profit. Use the Income Tax Calculator to estimate your total federal income tax liability separately.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">When are quarterly estimated tax payments due?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The IRS generally requires quarterly estimated tax payments on April 15, June 15, September 15, and January 15 of the following year. These payments cover both self-employment tax and federal income tax on self-employment income.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I deduct business expenses to reduce SE tax?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Legitimate business expenses reduce your net profit, which directly reduces the income subject to SE tax. Common deductible expenses include home office, mileage, equipment, software subscriptions, and professional fees. Always keep records and consult a tax professional for your specific situation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="related-section">
